1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":22,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":67,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Wyham was born in 1315, in Wyham with Caldeby, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Robert de Wyham, was 30 and his mother, Henrietta de Mortaigne, was 26. He married Beatrice de Rye about 1352, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 23 February 1391, in Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76, and was buried in Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1315–23 February 1391":"1315–23. veebruar 1391","1315–1391":"1315–1391","1315–1390":"1315–1390","1354–1424":"1354–1424","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","November 1390":"november 1390","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","23 February 1391":"23. veebruar 1391","1424":"1424","after 23 February 1391":"pärast 23. veebruari 1391","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","about 1352":"umbes 1352","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Wyham with Caldeby, Lincolnshire, England":"Wyham with Caldeby, Lincolnshire, England","Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England":"Gosberton, Lincolnshire, England","Wyham-with-Caldeby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Sleaford, Lincolnshire, England":"Sleaford, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1315–23 February 1391":"1315–23. helmikuuta 1391","1315–1391":"1315–1391","1315–1390":"1315–1390","1354–1424":"1354–1424","1285–Male":"1285–Kuollut","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","November 1390":"marraskuu 1390","1285":"1285","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1337":"1337","23 February 1391":"23. helmikuuta 1391","1424":"1424","after 23 February 1391":"23. helmikuuta 1391 jälkeen","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","about 1352":"noin 1352","1328":"1328","